Vladimir Putin and the risk of a third world war
San Francisco – February 24, the Russian invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of the third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a long meeting on February 4 – the day was the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries, which was carefully drafted.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires prior detailed negotiations.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and wage war in Ukraine.
He believes that confirming himself as China's lifelong ruler in the second half of the year is just a formality, and he is certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi has carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to achieve his lifelong dream in an astonishingly barbaric manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin thinks that if he wants to leave a lasting legacy in Russian history, it's now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to think that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This system is the opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the emotionally and sentimentally Russian people to an extreme degree.
In my childhood, I had many encounters with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I called my political charitable career.
Initially, I established a foundation in my homeland of Hungary, and then actively participated in promoting the activities that led to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, I even established a foundation before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square Massacre).
I don't personally know Putin, but I've been closely following his rise to power and am well aware of his cold and ruthless character.
He flattened the Chechen capital of Grozny, and now he's threatening to do the same to Kiev, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a clever KGB agent, but he seems to have changed in recent times.
He seems to have lost touch with reality, as he has formed a fixed idea.
It is beyond doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainians who speak Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in reality, they are no different from Ukrainians who speak Ukrainian.
In the face of what seemed like an overwhelming possibility, the Ukrainian people still put up an astonishingly brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kiev is the site of the original Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not entirely without historical basis.
But in the second part of the content, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians had bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that broke out in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But when the Russian military received the order to attack his Ukrainian brothers, they performed poorly.
The defense ministry's grant of simultaneous deep-seated corruption also played a crucial role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only didn't blame himself, but rather seemed to have gone mad.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be unconstrained.
He threw the entire Russian military into battle, disregarding all combat rules, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The US and the EU are shipping defensive weapons to Ukraine while trying to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has achieved a miracle in bolstering European resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has gone off track.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship was still "firm as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to exercise maximum restraint in the war.
It is still impossible to determine whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that before they destroy our civilization, Putin and Xi will be ousted.
